Redundant staff at compensation body awarded ten times that handed to victims
Staff at the Government's criminal injuries body are being handed voluntary redundancy packages tens times the size of the average compensation awarded to victims of violence.
By Tom Whitehead, Home Affairs Editor
7:00AM BST 30 Sep 2010
A total of £868,000 was paid in so-called early release schemes for 14 employees of the Criminal Injuries Compensation Authority (CICA) last year – an average of £62,000 each. At the same, around 31,500 victims of violent crime shared compensation payments from the authority of £209 million – and average of just over £6,600 each. Critics said the pay-offs for staff would be better spent helping victims of crime. CICA is the Government funded body responsible for assessing and awarding compensation claims for victims of violent crime. But it has faced regular criticism over the level of payments often given to victims. Related Articles
Government to slash cash payouts for crime victims
29 May 2011
Last month it emerged a nurse who was robbed, tied up and left for dead in her own car boot had been offered only £3,000 in compensation – a similar amount to that awarded to convicted criminals who were forced to slop out their own cells. In July it was disclosed that seven victims of the 7/7 bombings in London are still awaiting deals on compensation payouts nearly five years after the terrorist attacks. Blair Gibbs, Head of Policy Exchange’s Crime & Justice Unit, said: “Crime victims often struggle to receive adequate compensation, and the criminal injuries scheme remains bureaucratic and very inefficient at awarding payments quickly. "Money spent on pay-offs for these managers could have gone towards helping victims of violent crime.” A CICA spokesman said: “We are working with the Ministry of Justice to deliver a better service for blameless victims of violent crime. “Last year we resolved more cases, more quickly while cutting our administration costs. Departmental early release schemes help us cut future costs by reducing the number of staff.” Law and Order
