Gordon Strachan's Scotland squad full of quality, says Andy Webster as he refutes Craig Levein's claims
Among the many self-serving claims made by former Scotland manager Craig Levein in recent weeks is that he failed because the players he had at his disposal were simply not up to the job.
Leaps to the defence: Andy Webster says the quality in Scotland's squad is exceptionally high Photo: DAVID MOIR	By Ewing Grahame
9:35PM GMT 07 Feb 2013
Comments
Midfield, he claimed, was the only area where he enjoyed an abundance of quality: the defence and strikers were, he implied, not fit for purpose. Of course, what he really meant was the fact that he had won only three qualifying matches out of 12 (against Liechtenstein twice and Lithuania, all by a single goal) was the fault of the aforementioned players and that no blame could be attached to him. It is, of course, an argument with far more holes in it than the rearguard he complained about having to work with and one which was unlikely to find favour with those players he left behind. Hearts centre-half Andy Webster diplomatically declined to make the case for the Scotland defence but was quite prepared to argue on behalf of the nation’s forwards. “I think the quality in the squad is exceptionally high,” he said. “Even with the changes the manager made [to face Estonia] he was bringing on boys who are playing in the Premier League every week. Related Articles
Best of British football stamps
08 Feb 2013
Scotland 1 Estonia 0
06 Feb 2013
Strachan takes first step as Scotland boss
05 Feb 2013
Brown relishes being guest of honour
05 Feb 2013
Scott Brown named Scotland captain
05 Feb 2013
Strachan grilled on steak bake, chips and Elvis
04 Feb 2013
“So if you have that sort of strength in depth it’s only going to help as a team. You can call on that if and when required. “There is a lot of quality throughout the squad. Look up front and Steven Fletcher has started the game with Shaun Maloney and Steven Naismith in behind. “We have Jamie Mackie there as well, boys who are playing in the Premier League week in and week out. “Kenny Miller also offers experience so it must be nice for the manager to be able to call upon these people if and when they are required.”
Webster won his 28th cap at Pittodrie but it became a landmark occasion for the 30-year-old when he was handed the captain’s armband by Scott Brown upon the Celtic midfielder’s substitution. “It was nice to get the armband,” he said. “Any time you captain your country it’s an honour. It was good to get that opportunity because not many people do. “Of course, it was different from actually leading your team out but it doesn’t really alter the way you approach your job. You still do the same stuff and conduct yourself in the same manner, but it’s a nice touch. “There is a lot of quality in this team , a lot of boys you would look at and you wouldn’t argue with them getting the armband. So, from that point of view, it could have been any one of us.”
Webster claimed that Gordon Strachan had been pleased by the efforts of the players, who gave him his first victory in a managerial debut, a feat he had previously failed to achieve with Coventry City, Southampton, Celtic or Middlesbrough. “In the first half we kept the ball reasonably well under difficult circumstances,” he said. “In the second half we changed it round a little and they put us under a bit more pressure but I thought we coped with that reasonably well. “It was nice to get off to a good start under a new manager. You come and join up with the squad and even the boys who have been injured have made the effort to do that. “It is important to get that collective team spirit together and it’s important to show the manager what you can do.”
Webster certainly believes that things can only get better under Strachan once the manager, who turns 56 on Saturday, has the opportunity to transmit his ides to the group in more detail. “The difficult thing with international management is the short period of time you have,” he said. “Obviously, what we have done leading up to the game let us work on one or two things. It planted the seeds for people to think about it. “When you get to this level, though, sometimes the players have to take responsibility. You go out there and have to make decisions: that’s what you are judged on as a footballer. “So I think the manager has implemented his ideas, which the boys have taken on board. Marry that with the quality we have and, hopefully, that will stand us in good stead.”
